news.title: Doyoutravel
news.text: I just spent my last 3 days in Thailand up in Chiang Rai. Captive elephants are a touchy subject (and for good reason) however over the last 3 days I learnt a lot about these beautiful creatures, the history of captive elephants, and the amazing work done by the team at this resort. Of course in an ideal world there would be no captive elephants. Elephants are meant to be in the wild but that‚Äôs simply not possible due to past circumstances. For thousands of years elephants have been captivated, mistreated and used for various inhumane reasons across Thailand. At Anantara all elephants have been rescued from illegal logging camps and elephant shows. They cannot be set free in the wild for obvious reasons, so the next best thing is being well looked after at ethical elephant camps like this one where they‚Äôre cared for, rehabilitated, and able to roam freely. If you do decide to visit an elephant sanctuary during your travels please do your research first and make sure you‚Äôre taking part in ethical places only!

news.title: youngadventuress
news.text: I began blogging full-time back in 2013, long before getting paid to travel was really a thing. While it seems like a lifetime ago now, it took many years of hard lessons, setbacks and failures for me to grow and step into my current role. For years my time and my work didn't seem valuable to me, and I happily accepted cheaply paid writing gigs and free trips, stoked that I was living on my own terms with creative freedom. I nodded when people told me I was lucky and didn't think twice about working towards a real income; I was just so grateful for what I had üôèüèª But instead of living like a queen in Bali, I chose to settle in New Zealand, the land of $7 avocados and $100 tanks of fuel; free trips didn't pay the bills and the time it took from me kept me from pursuing other paid work üôà I scraped by making ends meet, living on 2 minute spicy thai noodles and juggling bills week to week, believing myself fortunate, and often doing so much more work than I needed to without earning a dollar. I convinced myself that it was good for my brand long-term, and I was building my reputation, changing an industry took time, right? It took getting massively taken advantage of and fucked over by a business I was close to for me to finally wake up and find some goddamn self respect ‚úåüèª Dear baby Liz, just because the work you do is on the internet and totally new, doesn't mean it's not worth anything. Once the pain and hurt from that mistake began to ease, I completely changed my business. I set rates and fees and began looking at work opportunities through a new lens. No longer were they free gigs I should be grateful for, instead my time was worth something. It was terrifying to set these boundaries but once I did, my life and my income changed forever. Learn how to value yourself, and what I charge these days, and how to set prices for unique work with me in Queenstown at my next @thetravelbootcamp in October. Only two days left of early prices - get em while they‚Äôre hot üî•

news.title: youngadventuress
news.text: My favorite thing about my trip to Botswana is something you might not expect - meeting so many powerhouse women running their own businesses. You gotta love a savvy lady boss! It was SO COOL to connect with women in Botswana and hear their stories of hustling their dreams into reality. For example, I met Botlalo Keipeite in Gaborone, and she runs Thamaga Pottery, a female-led cooperative making handcrafted ceramic products. Over the years it has grown into a very cool non-profit that both preserve the traditional arts of Botswana and inspires creative women to come and train there. It‚Äôs also helping boost their economies through tourism too, establishing a standard of women in business in Botswana. Botlalo is proud of her designs and sharing her culture through art with others like me. It certainly galvanized me to get cracking on with some deeper personal projects that have been sitting on the back-burner. Supports many women entrepreneurs around Botswana, investing millions in partnership with the United Nations to aid with pushing for gender equality in the communities where they work and in their own business. By aiding women like Botlalo in honing and growing their businesses, not only is De Beers Group helping to advance women in Botswana, it's also establishing a future that is female. I love it!
